14. Ennius: Q. EnniuS, ‘the father of Roman poetry‚' was born at Rudiae in Calabria, in 239 B.C. Cato the Censor met him in Sar- dinia, where he had served in the Roman army during the second Punic war, and induced him to settle in Rome. There he lived thenceforth, honored and esteemed by the most prominent Romans of his time, notably the elder Africanus. Late in life he was granted Roman citizenship, then very difficult of acquisition. His fame rested principally upon his Annales, an epic poem on the history of

Rome, the first Latin hexameter verse. Only fragments of his poems surv1ve. ’
